TI  - Decision making and welfare effects in manufacturer's closed-loop supply chain for recycling and remanufacturing: A risk signal game theory perspective
AU  - Han, Yuliang
AU  - Liu, Wenchao
AU  - Han, Yuqing
AU  - Cao, Zhongwei
AU  - Ju, Jin
T2  - JOURNAL OF CLEANER PRODUCTION
AB  - In recent years, the progressive implementation of sustainable development strategies has positioned closed-loop supply chains as a prominent area of inquiry within supply chain management. This study develops a game-theoretic model of the supply chain comprising platform retailers and manufacturers, wherein retailers decide whether to disclose demand information, and manufacturers subsequently adopt risk-averse strategies and make decisions informed by the shared data. The results reveal several key insights: First, retailers are inclined to withhold demand information when manufacturers exhibit low risk aversion, whereas they are more likely to share such information when manufacturers demonstrate high risk aversion. Second, in scenarios characterized by low manufacturer risk aversion, the environmental impact is mitigated when information is shared. Additionally, under conditions of low risk aversion, withholding information leads to greater social welfare; however, as manufacturers' risk aversion intensifies, the strategy of information sharing becomes more socially beneficial. Third, the implementation of profit-sharing contracts enhances outcomes in contexts where information is not shared, although the magnitude of this improvement is constrained, given that the system approaches optimal under information-sharing regimes.
