TI  - Exploring sustainable models for green express packaging recycling with third-party involvement
AU  - Chen, Wei
AU  - Kang, Zengrui
AU  - Zhang, Dongqing
AU  - Zheng, Kaiming
T2  - COMPUTERS & INDUSTRIAL ENGINEERING
AB  - The rapid growth of e-commerce has intensified environmental concerns related to express packaging waste, particularly due to the challenges of designing effective recycling systems involving third-party recyclers. While their participation enhances recycling capacity, it also introduces complexity in aligning stakeholder incentives and responsibilities. This study develops a game-theoretic model to evaluate three governance structures- direct third-party recycling (T), manufacturer-delegated recycling (LT), and logistics-delegated recycling (MT)-and examines their impact on green investment, recycling performance, and profit distribution. Results show that differentiated pricing is more effective when remanufacturing savings are high, favoring Model LT; in contrast, Model MT performs better under low savings. Model T yields the highest profits for third-party recyclers, while LT benefits manufacturers and logistics providers. Cost-sharing structures also play a decisive role in shaping both environmental outcomes and stakeholder incentives. These findings offer practical insights for designing efficient and sustainable recycling systems under decentralized governance.
